-- Sub-Saharan African Equities: Eveready, Naiade, Safaricom, UBA Are Active
-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k   a n d   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 2010-10-04T15:32:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-04/sub-saharan-african-equities-eveready-naiade-safaricom-uba-are-active.html
The  Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share
Index    surged the most since March, rising 3 percent to
23,747.81 by the 1 p.m. close in Lagos.  Mauritius’s  SEMDEX Index  snapped two days of declines,
climbing 0.2 percent to 1,751.18 by the 1:30 p.m. close in Port
Louis. Kenya’s  All-Share Index  fell the most since Aug. 13,
dropping 1 percent to 81.83 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi.
Namibia’s  FTSE/Namibia Overall Index  retreated for a second day,
losing 0.1 percent to close at 794.84 by 4 p.m. in Windhoek. The
 Ghana Stock Exchange All-Share Index  snapped the longest streak
of gains since August, falling 1.9 percent to 6,812.75 by the 1
p.m. close in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. Stock symbols are in parentheses.  Eveready East Africa Ltd.  (EVRD KN), a Kenyan dry-cell
battery manufacturer, fell for the first time in three trading
days, retrating 5 cents, or 1.3 percent, to 3.8 shillings. The
company will fire 74 of its 316 employees because of
“prevailing business levels,” Managing Director  Steven Smith 
said in a statement on Nairobi-based Eveready’s website today.  Naiade Resorts Ltd.  (NRL MP), a Mauritian hotel operator,
surged the most since Sept. 28, rising 1 rupee, or 3.9 percent,
to 27 rupees. The company appointed Paul Jones as chief
executive officer, will increase the amount it plans to raise in
a share sale to 500 million rupees ($17 million) and is to issue
a further 500 million rupees of convertible bonds in a revised
plan to reduce its debt, it said in a stock-exchange statement
today.  Safaricom Ltd.  (SAFCOM KN), Kenya’s biggest mobile-network
operator, rose the most since Sept. 22, climbing 10 cents, or
2.3 percent to 4.55 shillings. The company received government
approval to buy IGO Wireless Ltd. and Instaconnect Ltd.,
Sterling Investment Bank ltd., a Nairobi-based brokerage said in
an e-mailed note to clients today.  United Bank for Africa Plc  (UBA NL), Nigeria’s fourth-
biggest lender, surged the most since June 9, climbing 45 kobo,
or 5 percent, to 9.9 naira. The bank sold bonds, raising 20
billion naira ($130 million) of so-called tier II capital that
regulators require banks to hold to protect depositors against
losses, it said in an e-mailed statement today.  To contact the reporters on this story:
